The Prague stock market has fallen to negative after trading
After the fall on Tuesday morning, the Prague stock market corrected its losses.
The transactions in ČEZ shares amounted to almost half of the usual daily trading volume.
On Tuesday, as soon as the market opened, the Prague stock market fell again from its previous day's fall of almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stock prices on Wall Street.
The market reaction to the vote of the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilisation plan, is thus also felt here.
The fall in Asian stocks
Asian stock markets fell dramatically on Tuesday, although indices managed to wipe out some of the losses during the day.
The Hang Seng Index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost four percent during trading, but later it wiped out some of the losses and reduced the drop to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises Index following the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange fell 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
The Sydney Stock Exchange was losing over five percent, but we finally managed to reduce the losses to 4.3 percent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation about the US bailout will affect financial markets around the world", observed Joseph Yam, head of the Hong Kong Monetary Authority.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are the same as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should soon resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, other countries could be affected.
The bloodbath of U.S. stocks
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected a financial system stimulus bill that would have cost up to $700 billion.
The lawmakers thus rejected President George Bush's call for support for the project.
According to Bush, the project should address the root causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks were in a bloodbath on Monday, and the major stock indexes fell to their lowest level in 20 years.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost nearly seven percent, having last fallen this far in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it became clear that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress gave in: the US government can inject $700 billion into the banks
The leaders of the US Congress and the government of President George W. Bush have agreed on a broader form of the financial assistance agreement to the US financial system.
It will be put to a vote early next week.
The US legislature made a decisive shift in the talks on the adoption of a bailout plan in the form of $700 billion in financial aid to the US financial system.
But success is not guaranteed.
Indeed, before the final version of the bill can be published and put to a vote, Congressmen must finalize a number of details of the agreement.
The financial system support plan will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Services Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
Sources say the plan should be put to a vote in the Senate by Wednesday at the earliest.
According to economists, the announcement of the rescue plan should be a major first psychological factor in reviving the financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms by which market support can be effective, there will be a 'disappointment'.
Paulson: The plan must work
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our differences about the form the market stabilisation package should take", said Nancy Pelosi, a Democrat.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislature met with U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson to finalize the government's structure.
The Commission should buy back from financial companies the unsellable real estate assets which cause financial undertakings considerable losses and threaten the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are about to agree on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
This market recovery plan still needs to be pursued, but I think we are there", says Paulson.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis has had a considerable impact on the falling stock markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, the lawmakers are working to get Congress to reach a final deal by Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are in the first time zone, where the Congress' decision could affect trading on Monday.
At the moment, however, it is impossible to say with certainty when the two Houses of the US Congress will vote, or whether negotiations will be blocked at the last minute by one or another problem.
The legislators hope that it will be passed in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still be subject to many changes.
The total amount of aid for the scheme must be divided into two parts.
The first 350 billion dollars, as President Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But if Congress feels that the program is not doing its job, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount in two steps: first an additional $100 billion, then, finally, $350 billion.
Mr Bush welcomed progress in negotiations
While the president can veto this decision, Congress has the ability to make it a minority decision.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain financing for the purchase of bad real estate bonds, whose value plummeted because hundreds of thousands of Americans were unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday", said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
President Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Mr Bush was pleased with the progress made on Saturday and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy".
Limitation of gold parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on the liability of the financial program, protection of taxpayers from losses, the deduction agreement, the timeline for the plan.
The new law also provides for a limit on the so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee to oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We have worked very hard on this issue and made significant progress toward an agreement that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans", Paulson said.
The plan also provides for assistance for property owners who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new installments for the mortgages it will buy back, while reducing the monthly payments of borrowers and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And this is because we don't know what the mechanism and the price of the buyback of distressed assets will be.
This will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government", says Marek this week on the server iHNed.cz.
Whether the plan is adopted now or early next week is not so important, according to Marek.
"It is far more important that Congress agree this week to support this plan and to enact it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, which provides for the adoption of the plan, is most important at the moment", Marek stressed.
A fight that has gone to extremes: MP3 players versus mobile phones.
We'll advise you how to choose
While virtually every cell phone can read MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Nevertheless, there are good reasons to get a freelance reader.
The choice depends entirely on the use and requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy a high-end, expensive gramophone for the house to play the new album by Maxim Turbulenc.
Firstly, such music products are not released on vinyl, and from a quality standpoint there is no objective reason for this to happen.
If you have a shelf full of vinyl records of art rock, jazz, and blues, you probably dream of at least one such phonograph.
The same goes for music on the go, which is compressed music, to put it in a simplified way - MP3 music.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan would find it difficult to stand headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, and there is enough room for everyone in between.
There's a lot to choose from.
Battery life is also crucial
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just playing music, but these are functions that are, of course, unknown to most mobiles.
No modern device is as universal as the telephone.
In addition to basic functions, such as telephone calls and texting, it is capable of playing and recording music and films, has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if you factor in smartphones and communicators, you'll have a small computer in your pocket.
Since no refrigerator can roast meat and no television will take pictures, we are witnessing a miracle.
The universal nature of the mobile phone has its drawbacks.
The more functions you use, the shorter the interval between charging.
And reading music is one of the most important energy buffers.
Few mobiles are capable of playing music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases much less.
In this respect, music players (especially the more basic ones) are much better.
In the case of cheap cell phones, expect them to play music for only a few hours.
If you also occasionally call, make sure you have a second charger for work - even for the most expensive devices.
This will not be a problem for MP3 players, which are capable of continuous operation for at least nine hours after being recharged, even if they are less efficient.
Another problem arises when recording music on the mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, especially since not all can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, you can record music directly onto the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without a charge, given the tiny size of the memory cards used in mobile phones.
As far as the players are concerned, you do not need any software, except for the iPod.
All you have to do is fill the music player from the computer via the USB connector.
Most mobile devices and players will create a media library of their own, sorted by artist name, album title, style, or user judgment.
Some devices display only one index with a tree structure, like Windows Explorer, while others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to manipulate, mobiles are more skilled
When choosing a particular device, you should be particularly interested in the battery life, memory capacity, sound quality and output type and, of course, ease of control.
If music is basically background noise to you and you're going to listen to it for a limited time during the day, like when you're on the tram, you just need any mobile phone that plays MP3s.
Almost any motive today is capable of doing this.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or the player can play.
Everyone can play MP3s and the vast majority of music that will reach you will be in that format.
It is one of the most common formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA music.
AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods) is less common.
High-end mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding operator's (or another provider's) web pages from your mobile phone and buy the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a musical motive.
The supply of operators is unfortunately poor and is in most cases limited to quick-made radiotubes.
The prices are not the lowest either.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether via GSM, the Internet or even the wireless Internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people still carry their cell phone on them.
Whenever you want to listen to something, you just take out your phone from your pocket, when you forgot your MP3 player at home.
It is also important if you always have earphones or a handsfree with a connection.
If not, you can use the built-in speakers, which almost all mobile phones have, but at least MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of musical instruments is their price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
For the price of three thousand four thousand crowns, you can get a walkman that is already very convenient.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of an outlet for ordinary headphones.
The price of the best and best equipped telephones, with an entry for ordinary headphones, is not more than fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of being easy to control.
Anyone can order the most basic readers - which may not be the cheapest (see our choice).
Minimum functions; and the similarity of the control to that of a cassette recorder, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There's no risk of collision in the form of a randomly connected mobile internet, followed by a huge data bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for interchangeable memory cards (M2 type, microSD, etc.).
Even if you include the additional cost of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand kroner.
But be careful.
The basic models generally only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive ones can even handle 8 GB memory cards.
If you already have a cell phone and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, get a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or a River.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1 100 kroner.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman phones (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent MP3 control keys, and thus the ease of control is close to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose Walkman series phones have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, has gone the furthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
The first virtual operator will be launched in the Czech Republic this year.
- Maybe you did.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
However, we are still missing something - a virtual operator, which would force conventional operators to lower prices.
He may not be gone for long.
We have already mentioned many times on Mobil.cz that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) reported that the price of an SMS was higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
The latest steps taken by the European Commission to regulate roaming charges are likely to lead to a paradoxical situation - some Czech mobile operators will find SMS messages sent from abroad cheaper than domestically.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high, compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is a lack of competition that would really want to get into the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration rate well above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Board of the Czech Telecommunications Authority (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that there is no more room for another operator in the Czech Republic, joined the operators.
It is probably true that a conventional operator with its own network seems to have little luck (in fact, it would be difficult to find frequencies now).
There is still a possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable fall in prices, to which conventional operators had to respond.
Yet even before the advent of such trouble makers as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile, voices similar to those we hear at home today were heard in Britain.
However, it turned out that there was still room for such operators and that they could be really successful.
We do not have to look too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the country.
The Commission has also taken the view that the Commission's proposal to set up a European network of telecommunications operators is not appropriate.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more specific target group.
For them to operate efficiently, they need far fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
This is how, globally, virtual operators are positioning themselves as low-cost operators - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often offset by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Britain offers SMS services at at least twice the price of its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, targeting an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
This operator is specifically targeting men.
"Real men choose Mobilking - a carrier they like and trust", says David Seibert, CEO of the Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual carrier.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work here too.
The Commission notes that the Czech Republic has not yet adopted a comprehensive approach to the market for the provision of services to the telecommunications industry.
This is particularly so since it is relatively saturated in terms of service provision".
No chance in the Czech Republic, say mobile operators
It seems almost certain, however, that if there is to be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our region", said Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, in a telephone interview with Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were not in favour of this idea.
Instead, they try to do everything they can to prevent a potential competitor from appearing.
The GTS Novera group, which is thus taking a new step towards becoming a real competitor of Telefonika in the business customer sector, has made it clear for some time that it intends to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have already held several negotiations with all Czech mobile operators on this possibility.
With some of them we have managed to make progress in the negotiations", says Pavel Kaidl, spokesman for the group.
So the future may be bright.
From unofficial reports, it seems that we could perhaps welcome the first virtual operator as early as the end of the year.
But for now, his creation is accompanied by complete silence.
'At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is very specific compared to others.
So far, no subject with a complex and serious project in this area has contacted us", said Vlastimil Sršeň from the press department of Telefonika O2, in a statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet registered a viable and bilaterally beneficial project that could serve as a basis".
It adds: 'It is virtually impossible that a virtual operator will appear on the T-Mobile network before the end of the year.
To operate in such a short time, we should have a concrete agreement now".
The Commission notes that the Commission has not yet received any information on the compatibility of the aid with the internal market.
Miroslav Čepický says in this regard: 'We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared fees and infrastructure.
This is what we believe means the most input from the customer's point of view.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for high-speed mobile internet.'
Responsible authorities: in step with operators
The approach of the mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean increased competition, would have led to lower prices and thus to a decrease in their profit.
What's the point of facilitating the rise of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators can get along like fair thieves, as is evident from the quarrel surrounding the creation of U:fon.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTÚ, when U:fon was created, was exerted by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ's website.
Today, however, U:fon is being used as an argument against accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová commented on this: 'Competition on the mobile market has also recently been increased by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the RT mobile market, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would place high demands on it, especially on its services.'
But given the attitude of these mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulatory bodies seems puzzling.
This is not the only case of the attitude of the ČTÚ, which unfortunately, unlike Britain and other developed countries, has no power to intervene in economic competition in the Czech Republic.
It is the exclusive property of the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
The latter, however, took his typical position on this issue.
'The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator concerned on the lease of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been reached at the moment, as the offer from potential interested parties has not been sufficiently attractive to conventional operators", said Kristián Chalupa from the ÚOHS's External Relations Department in response to our question.
A statement of this kind would not be surprising from the operators' representatives.
But such a statement from an agency which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, ensure that no one takes advantage of its position on the market is more than confusing.
Kristián Chalupa adds: "In other countries, where virtual operators are normally present, their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile telephone services".
However, it is not in the interest of ÚOHS to press for fair market operation and lower prices.
What is shocking is the almost touching agreement of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, naturally arises.
In the same way, a price for petrol which is strictly the same at all filling stations is probably due to chance and the fierce competition.
'The Office has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this respect and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore no corresponding increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The telecommunications regulator probably lacks the tools to open up the mobile market to virtual operators", Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position on the market is one of the many points of disagreement.
There is of course an analysis of the relevant markets by ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view: in order to create a virtual operator, the consent of the network operator must be obtained at all times.
And the mobile operator has a pretty logical monopoly on its network.
It is therefore necessary that it should play a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
Even without accepting this argument, it should at least be of concern to ÚOHS that three mobile operators are clearly acting in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including the GTS Novera company, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Putting the blame on ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in communications, by which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have seen this kind of attitude in a number of similar cases.
Unfortunately, the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act did not extend the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many experts promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this very well, but their interests seem to lie elsewhere.
When no one's looking, it can work.
However, the operation of a kind of virtual operators, several of which are on Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, these are companies involved in multi-level marketing.
Specialised mobile telephone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms are usually only available to elected officials.
The trick is that the company is presented as a conventional business customer who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As a major customer, she gets special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you are saying happens, it could be a breach of the terms of the contract that we would look into and could result in the termination of the cooperation with the company in question", Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
Nevertheless, it is unlikely that such activity has not reached the heads of mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three companies mentioned above, it may be thousands of customers.
However, no operator is opposed to such a procedure.
The activities of these firms bring them considerable profits and, at the same time, unlike genuine virtual operators, they do not threaten them in any way with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but the services of these companies are used by only a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered in their name and therefore they cannot have full control over it, as do ordinary mobile phone customers".
But that is precisely what should seem strange to the ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises at the ÚOHS.
If mobile operators are turning a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively wide powers to disclose such activity, and that it will not be content with explanations from operators who claim to have no idea that this would happen, as their contractual conditions prohibit it.
When we're no longer the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has led to a considerable drop in the price of services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators appeared, however, the conventional operators made little or no effort to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were virtually the same - too small or too saturated a market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
But it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries have intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they eventually achieved the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities treat this issue like a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it to a nearby target.
In our experience we cannot escape the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial in these cases.
But let's not throw the sleeve after the axe.
If the behind-the-scenes news is true and a virtual operator soon appears in our country, the Czech mobile market may be back on track.
If one operator has agreed to the creation of a virtual mobile operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain unmoved by the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech national anthem has four new versions.
Choose the Best
Listen to the four performances of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of the Day of Czech Citizenship, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with a male or female solo singer, a chorus and an instrumental version.
The vocals are provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the composers of the arrangements.
You can listen to the four new versions on the server iHNed.cz.
Bělohlávek considers the Czech national anthem as one of the most beautiful hymns.
As he had previously entrusted to Český rozhlas (the Czech public radio), he chose for the solo performances singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers and the choir had a good diction, so that the words were understood, that they sang simultaneously", he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj was first performed in 1834 on the stages of Stavovské divadlo (the State Theatre) in Fidlovačka (The Saviors' Kermesse), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, with music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously took it.
After the creation of Czechoslovakia in 1918, the first verse naturally became an integral part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
