Prague's public transport (MHD) will introduce the chip in its ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday 1 October 2008 will be recorded in the history of the Pražský Dopravní podnik (Prague Transport Agency) as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who will have an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day coupon (valid from 1 January 2009) and have it registered on their smart card at the information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency) located at Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl, Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka metro stations.
From yesterday, it is also possible to buy coupons online on the Dopravní podnik's website: www.dpp.cz.
Over four hundred people enjoyed the morning service.
Those who start using the online shop can forget about the ticket counters in the metro stations, where they have so far had to eagerly step in long lines to get paper tickets.
They will buy their voucher online and it will be registered on their Opencard card in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"At these contact points, passengers have a ticket office with trained staff, who will help them with their online purchases and also save the voucher they have purchased on their card", says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to libraries, it will also be possible to register electronic vouchers on the Opencard in ATMs in the lobby of several metro stations.
What do these vending machines look like?
They are red, reminds one of the ticket compositing machines, and passengers may have already noticed them at the Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská metro stations.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty", Opatrný added.
An automaton will control the coupon for the driver
The machines that will be operational from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply insert the Opencard chip card and the previously purchased coupon will automatically register on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital but also in the surrounding area.
The main use of the buses is for the suburban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which are mainly used by the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia to access the capital.
"On trains integrated into Pražská integrovaná doprava (Prague integrated transport), controllers are equipped with card readers, which they use to establish the temporary and zonal validity of the tickets", said ticket controller Filip Drápal of Ropid, which designs Prague public transport timetables.
Suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated in the driver's cab.
When boarding, it is therefore necessary not only to show the smartcard to the driver, but also to place the Opencard in the indicated place on the side of the trunk.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"If the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing simpler than asking the driver for this information", Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take the suburban buses and do not remember the expiry date of their voucher can re-join the ATMs, which were originally used to save the vouchers on the card.
This is where the information on the validity of their document will be displayed on the screen.
Sudetenlanders were calling for a referendum in the US
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that Šumava be incorporated into the United States.
This is shown by a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we want at least to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the president of the United States with such a desire.
This is evidenced, among other things, by a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
In the letter, Germans from Český Krumlov asked the US president not to allow the "šumavská župa" (forest region south of Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have a clear understanding of the situation and want to be sure that the words proclaiming that American troops are coming to German territory are not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators", the letter, signed "Persons who care about the fate of the Šumava", reads.
Since the alleged promise of joining Czechoslovakia - given the Czech national character - is nothing but brutality, recklessness, incomprehension, oppression and servitude, the letter's authors urge the US president to take the Šumava protectorate into his own hands now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a foreign state, which oppresses and destroys minorities and has done nothing to help the Allies win without taking into account the opinion of a quarter of a million inhabitants", the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is fear of revenge from the "Czech oppressors".
If the US president doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would have to organise, according to the letter's authors, a referendum in the region to determine whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the US or live under US patronage.
Although the text in the letter may seem somewhat naive, given current knowledge of postwar history, according to some survivors, it well illustrates the expectations of Sudeten Germans at the time.
While the Czech Germans must have at least foreseen the possibility of expulsion from the republic, very few of them considered such a possibility.
Some expected the United States and Britain to give the Sudetenland some kind of autonomy.
Others thought they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, he was, as a German from České Budějovice, enlisted in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the British and placed in a concentration camp in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to him to learn Czech.
"They thought that when they returned home, the Czech language would be useful to them", says Chalupa.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war thought that the Beneš Decrees would expel them from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
A campaign to attack drivers
The most expensive road safety measure in Czech history.
A way of characterizing the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
The office of Minister Aleš Řebíček believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving.
This 150 million dollar campaign will be shown on television, radio, cinema, the Internet, and on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from speeding and drinking while driving.
But also remind them to fasten their seat belts before they start.
It is intended to reach the conscience of young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians and professional drivers.
What's going to be in the commercials?
Especially personal stories that will attack the emotions.
This is also reflected in the campaign's "bloody" slogan:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is written in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a pool of blood, there's the phrase "You'll pay".
Which must symbolize that one can pay with one's life for a moment of inattention.
The commercials will haunt viewers until 2010.
The ministry has taken inspiration from similar campaigns in the Anglo-Saxon countries, where images with harsh images of accident victims are common.
He believes this will lead to a reduction in the number of accidents and fatalities on Czech roads.
The commercials were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The strategy of sugar and whipping against drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time when they roast a red light.
The whip is a threat of a fine or an accident.
Drivers must be reminded of the risks", says Martin Kořán, transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is why we need information campaigns in the press, and especially negative advertising, says the psychologist.
He said that the warning signs to drivers are already less effective.
"When a static warning sign is installed, it will probably quickly blend in with the environment and drivers will not notice it", Kořán said.
Olmert would return almost all the occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the chairman of the Israeli provisional government, spoke in favour of returning virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made this statement in an interview published Monday by the daily Yedioth Ahronoth.
"We have to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all", Olmert told the daily.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to give the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), since without that, there will be no peace", he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Anyone who wants security in Jerusalem, and especially not to be trampled underfoot by tractors and bulldozers, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem", Olmert said, referring to the two attacks in the city in July that killed several people and injured dozens.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical sites" located inside the Old City.
"Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It will not work", he later stressed.
Withdrawal from the Golan Heights
Olmert also spoke in favour of Israel's withdrawal from the Golan Heights, which he considered an indispensable condition for concluding a peace agreement with Syria.
But this would also require some effort on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing peace with Syria solely on the basis of a Golan retreat", he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to abandon their current relations with Iran; they will have to abandon their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to abandon their constant support for the terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), Al-Qaeda (terrorist network), as well as Jihad (holy war) in Iraq", the Prime Minister said.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are flight attendants on the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; walking in a long-distance bus is forbidden
In the wake of the tragic bus accident at the Student Agency near Padua, Italy, the question arises as to whether stewards and passengers can travel inside the bus during the journey.
"If we want strict and formal compliance with the law, the activity of a steward is against the road traffic law", says Karel Hanzelka, spokesman for the Ministry of Transport.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old flight attendant died, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck that crossed the bus.
The girl was unfortunately sitting next to the driver in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had two other seats available.
But the bus can crash or even brake abruptly, even while the steward is serving coffee or distributing newspapers.
The important thing is whether the coach is equipped with standing seats or not.
If this equipment for standing passengers is not approved, passengers must remain seated.
The long-distance buses of the Student Agency do not have standing places, as confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by the company's director Radim Jančura.
"This is a matter we have discussed with the ministry and at first it forbids all travel of passengers.
Then they cancelled it and we got the passengers to go to the toilet during the journey as long as they have their own seat", he revealed his position.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no single legal interpretation of the steward's role - no legal prescription deals with this role.
Furthermore, there is no legal requirement to prohibit the carrier from offering services.
The Road Transport Act only defines the term 'vehicle receiver'; it does not define the rights and duties of the receiver", adds spokesman Hanzelka with more ambiguity.
Josef Pokorný, the head of the Road Traffic Department, believes that the law deals with the problem sufficiently.
"It all depends on whether the bus has standing passenger seating permits in its approval.
It's all in there", he said.
Buses are divided into urban, where there are standing places and a limited maximum speed, long-distance with standing places and a higher allowed speed and long-distance buses without standing places with the highest allowed maximum speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like flying, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert on transport safety at BESIP (Road Traffic Safety), does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"There is no danger in regular traffic, and the situation is comparable to that of airline service.
Here too, it is not certain when turbulence will occur and the flight attendant may hit her head".
"But if the bus had brake abruptly, the laws of physics would obviously apply.
Just like in a city bus or a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards by internal regulations", he says, adding that the problem is not solved from a legal point of view.
Jančura is ready to eliminate these services
Student Agency is the only coach carrier to offer steward services.
He hires two hundred.
Even after the accident, the manager doesn't consider their job a risky one.
"However, as soon as I feel that this is a risky occupation, I will remove it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper on board.
It would also reduce costs", he says.
The reason given for the absence of stewards in the car is safety concerns by Asiana's manager Alexei Litvine, who has a very small number of lines compared to SA.
"We have no hostesses, we have been against it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident", he told Týden.cz a year ago.
A great tragedy has come
A young flight attendant from the Plzeň area, who had worked for the company for two years, died in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency stop lane without using a flashing light and blocked the bus.
The driver of the latter tried to avoid him by means of a sudden maneuver, but he almost ran over him on his right side.
Jančura denies that the two seats reserved for the stewards' rest have been sold.
'In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked.'
The company plans to file a complaint against the truck driver.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the court's decision, but for the financial compensation, it also counts on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been being worked on for over a year by a group of 30 experts from the Ministry of Transport, could provide details on the travel of stewards on board the bus.
"But it has not reached any conclusion on this point.
In fact, it is not so much interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of mobile phones while driving", says Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally endanger the safety of passengers", concludes spokesman Hanzelka, adding that the police and the Office for Safety at Work are responsible for the safety of buses.
The hopes of the Dusseldorfer are now in Frankfurt.
The letter from the WestLB Management Committee to the employees of the company was full of bold words.
The merger of the entities of the Düsseldorf financial institution with the Frankfurt Deka-Bank could create the "central financial market institution of the Sparkasse financial group", according to the letter published on Monday.
WestLB would provide a 'competence block' doubled by sustainable productivity in such a case.
