Sleepless nights for the shareholders of Hypo Real Estate
The German banking system is relatively stable, the Federal Minister of Finance insisted just a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word "relatively" and that he was hinting that the German banking sector would not be spared the movements of crisis.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), listed on the DAX, obtained a 1 billion-dollar loan from a consortium of German banks to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person familiar with the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are being issued for up to 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction it would be entitled to.
The money comes from private banks as well as public banks.
In the background, it is the Depfa subsidiary that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible because of distrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's cash reserve had been reduced by 95% to EUR 2,37 million and the equity ratio had also weakened slightly from 1,6% to 1,45%.
Current and net profits from financial transactions were down by zero points compared with the same period last year, while profits from the allocation of loans and securities and the provisioning of credit operations fell by more than 70 per cent to EUR 5 million.
Only thanks to the substantial profits from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs resulting from the restructuring of the former Depfa group, as well as the reimbursement of interest under the tax procedure book and commercial purchases for Konzern companies, did the profit gap of around 16 per cent prove to be moderate.
After its privatisation in 1990, the former state financier had initially mis-speculated on industrial real estate loans, which were subsequently branched off to Aareal bank.
Because traditional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more involved in infrastructure projects and in financing joint projects between private and public investors (Private-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the subsidiary, Hypo Real Estate has to make depreciation which should have a material and substantial effect on the group's profit and loss calculation, but which remains rather vague.
The fact is, the dividends have been cut.
Already in 2007, they had been cut to two thirds.
Hypo Real Estate has been a very important state and infrastructure investor since the purchase of Depfa.
It is more robust than other institutions that rely on interbank refinancing because it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, lending between banks has again dried up considerably as banks have accumulated liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs a short-term refinancing facility for a part of the Depfa's total loans - about EUR 50 billion - each year.
According to a press release from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing needs are covered by medium-term credit and the company is protected from the influence of the largely non-operating international financial markets.
Other sources say that refinancing would be provided through the funds until the end of 2009.
HRE's Chairman of the Board of Directors Georg Funke, on the other hand, explained that Hypo Real Estate should no longer have to use the financial markets in the medium term.
The Bundesbank and the Federal Financial Supervisory Authority (BAFIN) assume that the market capacity of the Hypo Real Group is now assured.
The shareholders and creditors of the bank can only hope.
However, given the dynamics and the immensity of the crisis, there is no certainty.
It is not unthinkable that the whole of the financing should not be used.
But the opposite cannot be ruled out either.
The Bank is still on the verge of insolvency, according to the latest reports, late Sunday evening, so this at least temporary rescue will not be a satisfactory one either.
The share price fell by 75 percent to 3.30 euros.
Bond prices, on the other hand, are performing particularly well.
While the principal debts have barely moved, the prices of the secondary loans are falling.
The most affected are mainly the investment funds of the former subsidiary Württemberg Hypo and those that have a life span beyond 2009.
The bonds of Hypo Real Estate Bank previously appeared to be an alternative speculative investment, but their value must now be considered as dependent on the stability of the international banking system after the sharp worsening of the banking crisis and the crisis of the institution itself which brought the crisis into the institution by buying Depfa Bank.
As long as the less affected issuers, governments and commercial banks are still willing to support the system, it can be assumed that the arrears will be paid off over time.
Or it will happen what no one dares hope for at the moment - that the financial crisis can be overcome in the next 15 months.
But with the renewed rumors of partial nationalisation, the likelihood that was approaching certainty has now become a mere well-founded hope.
This should save sleepless nights for long-term creditors in deciding whether to part with their liabilities.
Short-term investors can still use what they have drawn to carry forward losses for the next few years on the next capital gains tax automatically levied on stock market gains.
