Rats have feelings too
If a rat or a cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean it feels fear too?
Neurophysician Joseph LeDoux is convinced that many animals have sensations too.
But how can we verify that he feels the same when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by renowned scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without proof?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness that I or anyone else has not been able to prove so far just as we cannot prove that other human beings have a conscience.
But in that case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and we address issues of feeling or consciousness in general, we enter into terrain that is difficult to work because the hardware doesn't match.
When faced with danger, a rat does what many other animals do: it kills, runs away, or attacks.
Humans behave in a similar way, which is why some scientists infer a similar subjective experience.
However, I do not believe that.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to translate our subjective experience into that of animals.
One aspect is that circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its involvement in short-term memory and in executive and directory functions).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and seems to be entirely absent in other creatures.
So at least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including our awareness of who we are, and our ability to predict and decide, it's reasonable to assume that humans are even different from other primates.
Another significant feature may lie in the linguistic nature of man: a large part of his existence being linked to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In that case, we could rule out animals.
But even if consciousness were not to be dependent on language, it would certainly be influenced by it, so that animal consciousness, however it is produced, would probably be very different from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is also difficult to determine what the conscience may look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, cannot be measured or, because of this particular hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, then its observation poses us big problems.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
You could look at the processes of consciousness in animals without considering the content, and that's exactly what happened in studies of short-term memory in primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach, which was developed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the neural correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Interestingly, this approach also highlights the importance of the prefrontal cortex in visualization.
But what does that do for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system like fear is activated in a brain that is aware of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is the state of mind we find ourselves in when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its effects, such as body reactions) takes over the vivid memory.
So, emotion is closely linked to the areas of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our fickle nature, are revealed, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to attribute to others than ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, believes that sensations from primitive activities originate in the cortex and brainstem regions of body sensation, as does Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
Since this network has not changed much over the course of human evolution, it could very well participate in all sorts of transverse sensations.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears to be fear in humans and rats is probably felt as fear in both cases: how could one test whether rats and humans feel the same when they behave in similar ways?
A cockroach runs away from danger, but what if it's afraid?
I don't think similar behavior is enough to prove identical experiences.
The nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brainstems, but cockroaches don't even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the source of sensations?
And even if we could prove this in humans, how could we prove it in rats?
I think rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are probably completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I prefer to explore emotional behavior rather than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, there is a significant improvement in the nervous system, as the same measurements are made in rats and humans.
Since I'm not exploring language and consciousness in rats, or sensations, I don't know if they exist.
You might think of it as a short-term challenge, but I'd rather move on than constantly bang myself against a wall.
I am indeed an emotional pragmatist.
