In a city apart, pride and the trials of black life
Hidden in the development of its vast park, a few miles from the sunny, glittering, giant Orlando, lies a quiet little town where the pride and complications of the African-American experience are born.
"Eatonville, first all-black town to be incorporated, childhood home of Zora Neale Hurston, that description she made in 1935 is not so simple to make nowadays. "The city with five lakes, three croquet courts, 300 dark skins, 300 good swimmers, full of guavas, two schools and no jail".
It has now become a pilgrimage town
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Zora Festival in Eatonville to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
And in many ways, the city she describes -- which became a tourist destination thanks to its inclusion in the Florida tourist guidebook published by The Depression-era Federal Writers' Project -- remains a place apart.
She is as independent, dignified, and private as she was in the 1930s, when Hurston said that the rural black population of Florida was often reluctant to share their true thoughts with the white man, who "knowing so little of us, doesn't know what he's missing".
Even though this is the year of the election of a black president, Senator Barack Obama, who has called for an open dialogue on race, many here remain wary of the outsider's gaze.
"We are very careful about how we tell the story", said Hortense Jones, 59, a longtime resident and the oldest parishioner in the city.
"it must be in line with reality.
Eatonville has long been defined as a paradox of triumph and struggle.
It represents both a historic model of a black takeover and a community of nearly 2,400 people where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a central point but also an example of rural Southern black culture - sometimes despised, sometimes hailed - that recalls the birth of American slavery.
Which would explain why the residents are both proud and protective.
The interest in the image of Eatonville born with Zora, who everyone here calls Hurston.
She introduced her hometown to the world through heartfelt, dialect-filled books such as "Mules and Men" (1935) and "Their Eyes Were Watching God" (1937).
Five paragraphs in the Florida guidebook transformed this town, located just off of Highway 17, a road that runs through the center of Florida, often forgotten, and that ends in a chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold as a big box in life and literature, Hurston led readers to the store owned by the first mayor of Eatonville, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was then divided into several private parts.
"On the left", she writes, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its gardens and those well-kept playgrounds that Howard Miller has always cared for, although he can barely read and write.
She further mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn" sells drinks of all kinds as well as anything that can serve passersby.
So in just a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn't actually a portrait that everyone appreciated.
Zora described the reality well", said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of the Johnson girls Hurston immortalized, citing the colorless songs performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: "Some people didn't like it".
Hurston is still remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who returned frequently after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town unannounced in a large Chevy, cigarette in his mouth and pants on, where even today, people are proud of traditional clothing.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many laughed at her.
"people were always happy to see Zora", he said.
But he adds, swinging in his back-patio chair overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was likely baptized, that "she never stayed too long".
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in some sort of grave in Fort Pierce, Fla., where she lived.
In Eatonville, there's no big memorial service, no plaque for the general public.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy she offered the world", said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows", a 2003 biography of Hurston.
A crucial moment came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to build a five-lane freeway in the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's main two-lane street.
Orlando's development has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made as Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, has ended the community's relatively idyllic isolation.
In the 1950s, the race rift led to hatred at the gates of the community.
"at that time a bunch of white youths would come and throw oranges or objects at people sitting on the side", said Mr. Franklin.
"a lady even died".
They threw a watermelon out of their car".
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration, calling its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "insulting rather than glorifying my race".
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some respects, has diluted Eatonville's cohesion and weakened youth confidence.
"Black children used to be kissed - I remember - we kissed our teacher in the morning, and in the evening too", said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and chief executive of the Eatonville Community Guard, a nonprofit group.
This went on, she added, until the teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You don't kiss your white teacher because he's white - I mean there's a cultural line here", said Miss Nathiri.
Civil rights, by the way, have created space for many other Zora Neale Hurston - black writers, actors and artists who have gone beyond prejudice, like her, armed with a joyful self-confidence and guidelines such as: "How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!"
I can't believe this".
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited Hurston's unmarked grave and began a struggle to revive his reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a best-seller, reintroduced her to the American cannon.
The highway project came just as Eatonville's most famous girl had regained her appeal.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors see her as a savior.
The community began holding a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of this highway.
