"I photograph the master off stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no clothes of the woods.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, free from all tension to achieve the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On one side, the artist.
The other person.
Inseparable except in the privacy of those moments unknown to the general public, when you discover by intimate gestures and stolen gazes artists who don't mind getting on stage.
German artist Günther Bauer mixes the theatricality of a few performances with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of the artists in "Flamenco - people".
In this project, the photographer takes the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programme of Flemish Photography Month, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, which grows every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that these are not typical images of performers on stage.
These people photographed "on the street" are artists capable of conveying passion, sadness, joy on stage ... captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists you don't have to take pictures on stage.
They have their own personalities and character.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera moments of the personality of the flamenco stars".
With the Festival "Song populaire des mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, are reminiscent of classical photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the dance or the singing itself, but the personality and character of the performer that captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and the magic has been the constant of this work that is being presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy photographed artists.
The project has evolved into an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, get to know them and be able to enter their lives for a moment or longer.
I think in photography, portraiture is the most difficult genre.
You're standing in front of people, characters that you sometimes don't know or that you only have a few minutes to take a picture of.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true".
This collection of portraits of contemporary flamenco, entitled "Flamenco - people", is on display at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at 20 Rue de la Mata (parallel to the Peupleraie d'Hercule) and will be open until 16 October.
