Repeat drinkers will have to install the alcohol lock system
The Home Office wants drivers who have more than three administrative penalties for alcohol in their vehicles to have a system installed in their vehicles that prevents them from starting the vehicle while drunk or not breathing.
The initiative was announced last June and is now reflected in the State Minister's report, which describes it as a pilot project for a year.
The aim is to reintegrate the driver into the workforce by offering him/her rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety will also be involved, along with the Directorate-General for Road Safety and the Institut Technological de la Sécurité de l'Automobile Foundation.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of drivers arrested for drunk driving more than once take up the wheel.
The alcohol lock would prevent this as it is a system plugged into the vehicle that measures the alcohol level in the breath and prevents the vehicle from starting if the driver does not breathe in first; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than the permitted level.
The cost is more than EUR 1.000 and is borne by the driver.
In this respect, a 2007 study in the United States showed that vehicles equipped with the system reduced offences by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that this could save 115 lives a year.
This measure is based on administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And to facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be done through ordinary channels but, however, reform through criminal channels requires reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some industrial and functional vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
The Congress of Deputies will vote tomorrow on an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party to install this system in school buses as it has been done in France.
