Talking in your sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I'm not talking about people who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but it doesn't really matter.
It's a mild sleep disorder called somniloquy.
It's quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure there's more than one who talks in the night.
This may occur very sporadically (once in a lifetime, for example, associated with a high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month, etc.), the day after the child no longer remembers anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence.
They are often associated with other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting, or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As mentioned earlier, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations, or overexcitation.
It's a little-studied phenomenon anyway.
The intensity with which it occurs also varies greatly.
He may speak in a small, quiet voice, with isolated words, whispers or, on the contrary, with shouts, cries, long speeches ...
If sleepwalking becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist to see if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for the problem.
We said it's a mild disorder, so there's no treatment unless it's related to another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it's related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to bed.
So look for games that are peaceful and avoid programs or TV series that are more or less violent.
With very nervous children who have difficulty relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down.
This will allow the child to sleep more peacefully.
As soon as you start sleepwalking, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Practical Advice
Don't wake him up.
It's no use, because he's unconscious and you'd wake him up.
Even though he talks, he's asleep and resting.
Remember, if the child is repeatedly showing signs of severe anxiety, it may be wise to see a doctor or to check what is causing the child's anxiety.
If you understand what he says (which is not usual), do not be tempted to ask him questions to get information.
You won't get anything, because when he's asleep, he's not conscious enough to organize his thoughts.
You will also hear what he says, but you will not know what he is dreaming about, so be careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you draw from it.
Never tell a child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even in a joke.
This causes a lot of anxiety.
In conclusion, do not worry, it is not a bad thing, it is an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
