Interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Hema-Québec has become one of the safest and most efficient blood suppliers in the world.
And most importantly, it has regained the public's trust, which had been seriously shaken by the contaminated blood scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood banks managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service were contaminated with the acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980's.
In response to this tragedy and the public outcry, the government of Canada instituted a public inquiry in February 1994, presided over by Justice Horace Krever, to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to prevent such a disaster from occurring again.
While Judge Krever was delaying his report, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee has fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were established in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began operations, only 38 percent of people still trusted the blood system in Quebec", recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and fieldwork over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence", she says, before proudly stating that by early 2008, almost 94% of the Quebec population now trusted Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary remembers that "trust is extremely fragile".
From the moment of its creation on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At the time, Europe was witnessing a large outbreak of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the agency that has been in charge since its founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know at all if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
One of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports was that when it is not known and a serious illness may result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by degeneration of the brain and inevitably leads to death, exclusion measures should be introduced.
In April 1999, blood was refused to those who had been in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
However, a few years ago it was shown beyond a doubt that the disease is transmitted by blood.
This incident showed us that the precautionary principle was sound".
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV test technique was introduced: the nucleic acid test (NAT), which detects directly the presence of the virus itself in the blood of donors, rather than antibodies against the virus, which were the basis of previous tests.
TANs have shortened the silent period between the time a person is infected and when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, she says.
This period was reduced to less than a week.
This has greatly reduced the risk that some donors may be infected without being aware of it and without being detected.
These improvements have greatly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from blood transfusions.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, this means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that today people can feel comfortable accepting or prescribing blood transfusions to get better", says the head of Hema-Québec.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island. Like the West Nile virus, it is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
The Commission has also been asked to provide a detailed description of the measures taken to ensure that the Community's energy supply is adequately supplied.
"Needs are increasing because the population is ageing.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need to be recharged with red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population is also affecting the blood donor network, which has an average of only 3 per cent of Quebecers eligible to donate blood".
However, anyone who is healthy, 18 years of age or older and who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 percent of people who donate their blood are not accepted, because they have AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they have traveled to a country where malaria is rampant, they will be excluded for a year.
"With this 3%, we manage to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to replace the members of this network of donors as they get older and can no longer donate their blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but it is especially difficult to deter and encourage them to become regular donors.
"In today's fast-paced world, it is rare to find time to give blood for an hour", laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for major burns.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord, once considered a biomedical waste, is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample a few weeks ago and plan to collect more than a thousand a year.
We should start offering them for transplantation early next year", says Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot access it", because Héma-Québec cannot afford to offer this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Québec.
