Free speech - The Orwellian discourse of Barrick Gold
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small, penniless publishing house in an attempt to launch a "transparent public debate".
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge by the truth, especially in cases of defamation, but by the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr Garver.
Because for Barrick Gold, the best way to conduct a public debate would be to bring ruin to anyone who dares to take a position contrary to his own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Black Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money to prepare their defence and fight, with very unequal arms, against an army of lawyers backed by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to bankrupt the defendants in order to impose a settlement that will gag the opposition and scare anyone who dares to look into the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view of the facts to the public.
Unlike in many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, debates in Canada are normally held by exchange of ideas, not by battering.
The mining industry had only to open its books, its files and start a real debate, through newspapers, the media, publications and funding independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems to distrust public opinion and repudiates petitions and letters of support for the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can both call for a public debate and disregard the opinions of that same public?
In the vice-presidential world, it seems that this word refers only to the well-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that's a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have a right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn't understand - or doesn't want to understand - is that the public that supports the writers and publishers of Black Canada is doing so primarily because they reject the brutal way mining is done.
This public is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in what many perceive as a gag-a-thon (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a notice to the authors of Black Canada instructing them to stop using the term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal rhetoric, the Barrick Gold lawsuit is a direct attack on academic research freedom and the search for truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
It denies, in its entirety, the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which are the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss topics that are not pleasing to the rich corporations of this world in a country like Canada, under the threat of repeated lawsuits, who will?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
She has a right to an answer.
The academic community, of which we are a part, has long been skilled at dealing with debate and disagreement and resolving conflict.
Barrick Gold's excessive prosecution makes it clear that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for a transparent debate.
This is a loss for the academic world, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
