Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
Her blue-eyed beauty was long her card asset, some would say her weakness.
Had he broken free of the narcissistic mirror, the charming American actor with the smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, sensitivity and uncanny talent must have also kept him from the register of power that breeds the true sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at age 83 of lung cancer at his Connecticut ranch, remains one of the last American film icons of the golden age.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and with whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his play, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breaking of dramatic conventions.
Blood-blends often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German Jewish father and a Hungarian mother.
From these European roots will emerge one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
No over-the-top ego, the ultimate in quality.
Because he was the self-made man of the country, the war veteran of the Pacific, wounded in action, who in the early 1950s studied drama at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in theater, television, and soon cinema.
This same civil rights activist was also the motor racing driver who finished second in the 1979 24 Hours of Le Mans, doubled as a sex symbol, although he was part of a model couple formed in 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
And with him, the shadowy parts of this secret, discreet, committed, show-business-allergic star, whose enigma has not been fully solved, disappear.
An honest man in the noblest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman has caused a stir among movie buffs this weekend as his major roles collide on the dark screen of memory.
More than half a century of a seventh American art in perpetual flux runs through him.
They come back to the memory of the charming cowboy in Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Hot Tin Roof adapted from Tennessee Williams in 1958.
Closer to Us (1990) tells the story of Mr. Bridge, a sensitive man troubled in his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all its promises.
So many other Paul Newman's have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role originally intended for James Dean, reprised after his death, which really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic villain in the brilliant The Sting, Oscar winner for best picture in 1973.
A bitter billiard player and a vengeful man in Robert Rossen's magnificent The Hustler (1961), he reprised his role on his return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar in 1987 out of nine nominations.
That face through the ages, that was him.
It's him again.
The times are changing along her journey.
Young people know him best through George Roy Hill's cult classic Slap Shot (1977) as Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
With a final role as the Irish mob's godfather in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the loop was closed.
Unlike many film legends who left the business early, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, denouncing Hollywood, its gold, its luxuries and its concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "a living challenge to the underplaying" judging his performances too strong.
The profession was not always easy for the handsome Paul Newman, whose roles had long been in his mouth.
He played the young starlets less often, however, than the outcasts: neurotic, alcoholic, bastard or desperate, whose perfect features reflected the deviations and rebellions.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known facets of his true modest sensibility.
His 1968 Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, painted a fine portrait of a melancholy woman.
He lost his son Scott to a drug overdose and dedicated his 1984 film Harry and Son to him.
In the rain of tributes to Newman yesterday, his close friend and former comrade in arms Robert Redford (they had acted together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said with great sadness: "His presence has made my life and this country better".
Generosity, love of existence are vivid traits of the late actor.
Beyond his legendary career, he is also a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester against Hollywood's deviations.
Many have seen the meatballs sit on pots of vinaigrette, sauces, biscuits and other foods, judging the process to be rather tasteless, though at first a bit of a hassle.
The profits from these sales were nevertheless paid to his Foundation for Children in Need.
Newman, rather than sit on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter that read: "Your father has always been incredibly grateful for his good star.
It was a privilege to be there".
And it's a privilege for us to have followed the path of such a lucid and generous American artist.
A model citizen, in short, and more.
What could Zuschlag &amp; Co. be making in their invoice factory ?
The hearings in the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin shortly, on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, having caused particularly significant damage.
The prosecution claimed that the money from the grants was used for personal purposes, while the benefits were justified by false invoices.
The state and municipal funds, totalling some HUF 65 million, went to the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and to the pockets of certain individuals.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to collect the money from the grants by issuing invoices for costs, behind which no real benefit was provided and thus the associations never met their commitments.
According to the indictment, most of the bills were forged.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books from the market in Józsefváros, while they manufactured the pills in Kiskunhalas.
The names of the companies to be included in the invoices were decided, inter alia, during the tours to the province north of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the man's statement, he was supposed to be looking for guesthouses and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he requested an invoice, on the basis of which they made the other invoices that they would submit, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, and the Capital Municipality to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who according to our information was mainly responsible for drafting the files necessary to obtain the grants.
On a "scouting trip", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag family in 2003, the restaurant catered for a group of 90 people, members of Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy the place at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which was later renamed Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was full of errors of form and substance.
A boarding house in Badacsonytomaj had in fact only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could stay there overnight.
The imaginative invoicers also went too far when they mentioned Pigal Kft, also in the Horeca sector, and neither Jobb Jövőért nor Hoppá appeared in their accounts, according to the information provided to the public prosecutor.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told hvg.hu that when the prosecutor's office called him and showed him the invoices, he knew immediately that they were fake documents.
"Our company name and tax number were misplaced on the stamp".
He added: "The fact that a hundred people stayed there, according to the bill, was not a good idea, either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which are not as spacious.
And the bill also says meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time".
The diligent invoicers also did not inquire about the travel agencies in Budapest, which were part of their choice but only arranged trips abroad, and thus naively reported stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which is also contrary to the agency's accounting practices.
Moreover, as was apparent during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, whereas the supplies concerning travel activities, the destination of which is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate on the four invoices drawn up on behalf of Hotel Révfülöp on behalf of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear VAT of 25% as indicated, but VAT of 15%.
The investigation by the Public Prosecutor's Office revealed that the 'issuers' also made mistakes in mentioning the transport of goods by road as a service, which the company issuing the invoices could not perform, since its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it was also for defective forms, such as inadequate invoice types and false stamps, that the invoices issued on behalf of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and Biztos Pont were found to be false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. and Kunfehértó's sports training centre, both of which deny that they are the authors of the invoices issued in their name.
The counterfeiters also failed to take into account the fact that HIB Kft., based in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation when (in 2001) the Fiatal Városértület Egyes group was supposed to have a meal at their house.
Invoices prepared deliberately
Another category of invoice issuers is those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapestért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the grouping of Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták, has issued an invoice for the sum of HUF 4 million to the Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Foundation.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was tricked into issuing false invoices by one of the defendants, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation, cooperated with the Zuschlags and in 2003 issued invoices to the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, Atlasz Egyesület and Vörösfenyő Egyesület for an amount of around HUF 5 million, but no benefits were actually provided.
No financial movement took place either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but this was not mentioned in the accounts.
The next category of invoicing companies is that of companies directly related to the defendants.
Thus, the administrative deputy of the managing director of Delta Trió Kft., which was in charge of the fuel and motor vehicle business, and whose registered office was in Budapest, but where he was not available, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, the company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment, amounting to about HUF 18 million.
The investigation showed that the equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of this company was a Romanian national, to whom Iván Kubatov also allegedly sent documents related to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány and that he pocketed their counter-value.
It was precisely at the request of Ivan Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies were functioning, which the defendant explained by the fact that they were not being given work.
He nevertheless made use of these companies, since at the request of Mr Zsolt Szente, co-accused and drafter of the company's instruments of incorporation, he issued invoices in their names, in the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the Atlasz and Y-Generáció associations.
Kubatov gave to the authorities 15 invoices in total, issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, for a value of HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecution thought that 10% of the amounts listed on the invoices plus the VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up dummy invoices which were used in Biztos Pont's subsidy application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a grant from the public utility of the Socialist Party, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this grant for a double amount of HUF 500 000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To avoid this being known, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were presented to the TMA.
In fact, these bills were found during a search of the office of Árpád Kemecsei at the Ministry of Education.
At the hearing, some of the defendants will relate the method of invoicing, as they had done before the prosecution earlier.
What might be really interesting is that the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to give details, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether it is in his interest, or if not, the Socialists have reached an agreement that in return for the repayment of a large part of the HUF 50 million, Zusi will wear the hat alone.
Today, he is probably annoyed, as the requests for his house arrest, based on a reduction in his conditions, are continually coming to a deaf ear.
While those who have caused far greater damage, and the perpetrators of irreparable economic crimes, are walking around freely or at least waiting in their own homes for the end of the proceedings.
The psychology of overbidding: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more and overvalue the goods.
Neuroscientists and economists at New York University have managed to update the neurological and economic foundations of this known and apparently irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, humans don't want to be left out of this kind of competition, like an eBay auction, and that's why they're even willing to pay too high a price.
This research has attempted to draw up a neurological pattern of this kind of "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lottery, while the other group took part in a fun auction, while researchers used an fMRI to analyze the active brain regions of the experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but during the auction, a key element of which is the one-third overbid, the whole under the brain stem, called the striatum, would move vigorously when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-stimulation" mechanism.
Therefore, researchers say, the reason for the price increases is the fear of the violent reaction of the striatum.
To support their theories, the economists in this group of researchers continued their financial surveillance analyses.
In these three groups, one partner was overbidden in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the actual value of the product in question, and they made their bet.
Another group was promised that if they won the game, they would receive an extra $15 as a reward.
While the third group received the $15 before the auction, the other group members also lost that money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is actually that the emphasis in one was on winning, while in the other, on failing.
In proving the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the "against failure" team were willing to place higher bets than those in the control group and the "for winning" group.
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any existing economic theory.
Each of these was based on the fact that the auctioning phenomena were based on the pleasure of winning and the risk of losing.
Only neurological imaging has helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories and now leads to a third explanation". - Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: When should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people have chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is the leading cause of death.
It is estimated that there are 100,000 patients with hepatitis in Hungary, but only 7,000 are being treated, because many patients are unaware that they are infected.
Hepatitis is a generic name for infections of the liver caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between the symptoms of hepatitis B and hepatitis C. While hepatitis B and hepatitis C are characteristic, the pathogens and the diseases they cause are different.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, are mainly spread in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and bodily fluids (sperm, vaginal secretions, saliva).
It is recommended that travellers get vaccinated against A and B viruses. There is no vaccine against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A usually appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor general health, weakness, stomach pain, and nausea.
Then a noticeable yellowing develops on the skin and white of the eye, the stool becomes lighter and the urine darkens in color.
Worldwide, one million people die each year from the most serious forms of this disease, such as cancer and cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason for this is that only about 1 in 10 people with this disease receive medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences. If left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they have the virus because the pathogenic gene destroys liver cells in a subtle way, and in many cases the first symptoms do not appear until 20 to 30 years of age.
Therefore, early prevention and regular screening are very important.
The infection rate is much higher than the average among a population of three groups: people who received blood transfusions before 1991, drug users, and tattooed people.
Currently, there are an estimated 200 million people worldwide with chronic hepatitis C.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory testing, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as you notice symptoms of unknown origin.
The disease can be cured if it is detected early enough, the virus can be eradicated from the body, the risk of infection disappears and cancer is prevented.
World Hepatitis Day is observed on 30 September and was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing patients from all over the world.
The aim is to draw attention to chronic cirrhosis of the liver, caused by viruses, its causes and the importance of early diagnosis.
Does one who believes in God feel less pain?
Recent research has shown that religious belief acts as a kind of painkiller, which has already helped make Catholic martyrs' deaths more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph reported that researchers at Oxford University conducted an interesting experiment to see how belief in God can influence a person's tolerance of pain.
In this odd experiment, 12 Catholics and as many atheists were subjected to electric shocks while each was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
The results showed that Catholics were able to avoid much suffering.
Using a technique of human brain palpation, it was also found that Catholics were able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first in a series of experiments involving academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different sectors of the university.
Specifically, the experiment is carried out as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and spreading the electric shocks is fixed on the left hand of the experiment subject.
The researchers asked the experiment participants to look sustainedly at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Hermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind the experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary would evoke a kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, was for its soothing effect.
The subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during that time, they received 20 electric shocks in four successive parts, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general-themed one.
Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary they felt "safe", "cared for", and "calmed down, and peace came over them".
When they saw the religious painting, they reported 12 percent less pain than when they were looking at Leonardo's work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image among atheists, provided that the appropriate photo is found.
"We should find an image that they respond to very positively, like a mother or a father", said the psychologist.
Tom Wright, an Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of this research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases actually changes our personality", Wright added.
After these excellent results, the only question remains, what effect would it have on the pain regulation of the subjects if we showed the faithful a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same calibre?
Would a better view of the Virgin Mary produce better results?
You are what you reveal about yourself.
For its tenth anniversary, Google says it can be found in the back of people's pockets just like the sky above their heads -- it knows where they've spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what their interests are.
But that's not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, one of the most influential people in the industry.
While skeptics who draw parallels with Orwell's vision of horror are missing the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to collect even more information about its users, which is necessary for the founders of Google to be able to meet their original goal: "Let's collect all the world's information in one system".
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of working to turn the world upside down, they are still only at the beginning of their goal of being able to process all information.
When asked what will happen in five years, Schmidt said he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What job would suit me best?" but software will only be able to answer this simple question when it knows enough about users.
It is not clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer that initiates the search and the pages subsequently accessed by the interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can see what they've searched for, what they've clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long run, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and our recorded preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my work is doing? users are asking, worried about Google's monopoly on information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can cause fear, and not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can provoke a backlash among Internet users.
However, it is a proven fact that the search terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases, they are passed on to a third party, and in such legal cases, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most notable example of this in recent times is probably the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information it had collected from the public page called Orkut, thus allowing identification.
Human rights-conscious netizens were relieved last May when Google, in league with the electronic legal protection organization EFF, proved its case in court against the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government has successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it won over the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier.
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is attacked by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their private sphere and private domain suffer when they start using Google services.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its "savages" of computer enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic users emerging in many countries see Google as the next generation of big business, the "fashion corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, which is being branded as the world's Windows invader, even though both are fighting for the same goal.
This may be because Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for an identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The document code and the continuously refreshed program package have a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, compared to the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see very accurately the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what Web 2.0, the most proclaimed keyword of recent years, is pulling right behind it.
The Web 2.0 is really about collaboration, about the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind us, and we use the communication channels that are at our disposal, and while the dimensions of these change one by one, the essence remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person can usually maintain a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and they can even link these to other services, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing their music habits. Then they can link these to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also maintain blogs, in which their latest photo galleries that they store on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
While there are many examples, such as the girlfriend who easily understands by seeing the morning photos taken by the circle of mutual friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or the company that fired an employee, just for the honest opinions he wrote on his blog about top management, one thing is certain: the term privacy is totally reconsidered these days.
The person who lives an online life is what they show about themselves, and that's how we can define the principle behind the behavior of today's youth.
Anyone who wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to get around Google's monopoly, can do so (by starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search engine, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that they cannot be traced is not small. Google online services, from word processing to image processing to reading information, can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not linked to huge server parks and do not fit our best profile, having existed until today.
The public is waiting, without really hiding it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with a current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). AdWords/AdSense advertising domains threaten advertising agencies' revenue, while services introduced at an increasing rate are causing serious migraines not only at Microsoft but at many other computer programmakers.
However, critics find that there are contradictions alongside all this with worrying effects: for example, the company's top management rejected, in its entirety, the employees' protests after it doubled the price of the company nursery and after the company deemed the daily multiple catering too expensive, taken at any time.
One of the company's internal rules is that new services are only announced when they can be used. What is certain is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world to new heights. While some people think that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project is getting so big that the company will soon be facing the U.S. Supreme Court, others are terrified of its health system, because in it, we can build a complete medical profit from our past test results, our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can provide a good raw material for the next generation of science fiction writers. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written in half-Orwellian tones, describes a future in which a man could be approached in a startling way just through Google data.
Two miners helped cover the tracks of the Ózd double murder
"The police have summoned two minors for questioning in the case of Ózd's double murder. Based on reasonable suspicions, they helped to cover up the crime", said the spokesman for the Borsod police department.
The young men have admitted to the charges against them, and are now being charged with complicity.
The two miners, who according to MTI (Hungarian Telegraph Agency) are young girls, are defending themselves.
As a contributor to murder, you can get up to five years in prison.
The suspect in the Ózd double homicide, a 23-year-old local man, was taken into custody on Sunday.
The charges against him are multiple homicide, premeditated and for profit.
During the investigation, it was revealed that the 23-year-old man owed a large sum of money to a 53-year-old man.
The suspect did not want to pay his debt and that is why he lured his creditor to a site in Ózd last Wednesday where he killed him and the man's 9-year-old daughter.
According to the information from the MTI, the young man had planned his crime, and the weapon with which he was going to commit his crimes, hidden at the crime scene, is proof of this.
The police are investigating the weapon and the circumstances of its use with the help of specialists.
The Warsaw Stock Exchange is proposing to buy the Prague Stock Exchange.
The Warsaw Stock Exchange offered two hundred million euros, about five billion Czech crowns, for the purchase of 100% of the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, chairman of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed this proposal made by the Poles despite the fact that the Czechs had previously excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the circle of new potential owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason for this exclusion is that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is in the hands of the State.
99% of the shares are held by the Polish State, which intends to divest more than 60% of its shares within a few months of the sale.
According to the Czech business daily E15, the Polish offer is the highest bid ever made for the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the Transatlantic Nasdaq Stock Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and the Deutsche Börse have all made an offer to date.
Petr Koblic, the director of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among the interested parties, the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the worst new owner, and did not rule out the possibility that this could lead to the disappearance of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague Stock Exchange is estimated by market experts at between 5 and 10 billion CZK.
Based on an agreement between the shareholders, some 90% of the shares would be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance with about 25 per cent stakes, followed by the bank Ceská Sporitelna with 14.7 per cent and Tiger Holding Four S. a.r.l. with 13.5 per cent.
The financial crisis from the perspective of the European press
In their Tuesday comments on the international financial crisis, which is worsening day by day, the leading European newspapers are already talking about a "second 9/11".
"The global financial disaster is the fault of the American president", says the Rome newspaper La Repubblica. "The president has not even been able to unite with his own party behind a hastily-made bill to help a desperate situation . . . "
Instead of a new Pearl Harbor, as billionaire Warren Buffett used to say, it's more appropriate to talk about a second 9/11.
Some of the Madrid press also see Washington as a scapegoat.
