The intelligent car mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What better way to develop technology to avoid obstacles than by mimicking an obstacle detector already in nature?
Like, for example, the bee.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC in Japan, the buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the strategic starting point to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired BR23C-type robotic self-driving system, which it has equipped with the qualities of bees, with the ultimate goal of encouraging the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During their flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped space, which in reality, closely resembles our secure protective shell - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, the head of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department, at the exhibition.
The bee's faceted eye plays a vital role, seeing in all directions at a 300-degree angle.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers have developed a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at a 180-degree angle and at a distance of 2 metres in front of the BR23C, it measures the distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns it into a avoidance maneuver.
The detection of the obstacle occurs in a fraction of a second, and then the miniature robot car, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system in existence today, this avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the mini-robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle", says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology is the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where collisions are currently considered inevitable.
All this process has to reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process must be in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference can't be up, down or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case we could only use rotational motion, acceleration and deceleration as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses Lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a larger energy concentration, making them longer-lasting than the Lithium-ion version.
Andoh says that it is the instinctive intelligent response that is paramount, not the processing of data, let alone the ability to store it.
This mechanism must process and react to only a few incoming signals per second.
It doesn't need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
You don't need memory with a gigabyte capacity, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing a technology for instant avoidance, which Nissan estimates will be introduced into mass-produced cars within the next decade.
Another application could be to incorporate it into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination by avoiding obstacles in his path.
