The written version of the $700 billion bailout plan to buy back bad credit from banks, and use it multiple times, is ready.
In the first round, half of that money will be spent.
Reuters reports that in new debates that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, local East Coast time, congressional leaders agreed on the days-long controversy surrounding a $700 billion bailout plan.
"We have made a serious step forward", said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the U.S. House of Representatives, who said the only thing left to do is put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born out of the plan, is supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
The US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said in a statement that the compromise would work and be effective, but that more work needed to be done. Pelosi said the plan was not to bail out Wall Street but to turn the economy around.
The written version of the plan was released before the Asian markets opened at 8pm local time in Washington on Sunday (or 2am Central European time on Monday), but did not cause the stock market to rise dramatically.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill called the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008, after which its fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the agreement.
"We are pleased with the progress made tonight, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy", said White House spokesman Tony Fratto.
The programme also differs from the original proposal made by the Bush administration, which stated that the $700 billion should be spent all at once on the repurchase of bonds on dubious loans.
From now on, up to half of the $700 billion can be spent, the first $250 billion will be released immediately after the bill passes Congress, probably on Monday, and the first $250 billion will be used by the Treasury Secretary to buy off the banks' dubious loans, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the chairman of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The second half of the $700 billion is dependent on a new congressional order.
Under the law, the Treasury secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: it will be able to simultaneously buy doubtful claims, securities for mortgages and doubtful mortgages, and other types of "toxic" claims.
The relevant persons in the Ministry stated that the purchases can take place in the context of an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the possibility of taking part in an insurance scheme, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that give rise to the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Henry Paulson said the law provides the tools needed to allocate $700 billion to the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it be the massive redemption of bad loans, their insurance, or to avoid the risk of the system causing the collapse of one or another major financial institution.
"We will make the necessary arrangements to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed", he added.
On the other hand, bank managers in dire straits who are waiting for state help can expect their severance payments, simply called the transatlantic golden parachute, to be capped by the government.
The limitations are also dependent on how the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the enterprise.
The cap principle means that if the Treasury secretariat buys out in an auction, they'll charge a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Immediately after the redemption of the bad debts, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to the leaders is not exaggerated.
The Commission has already taken a number of steps to ensure that the new agreements are implemented in a way that is consistent with the objectives of the programme.
This is the first time in U.S. history that legal limits will be in place on the appointment of chief executives, said House of Representatives Committee on Financial Services Chairman Barney Frank, a Democrat.
The government also acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks involved in the plan, thus reducing the risk to taxpayers, who may even be the winners once the economy and the bailed-out banks are back on their feet.
The bill states that within the next five years, the President must introduce a proposal to Congress that will determine how losses are to be reimbursed to taxpayers, starting with the financial sector.
There were, of course, those on both sides who expressed doubts about this plan.
That's not why the American people have mandated us, this doesn't protect taxpayer dollars", said Republican Congressman Darrell Issa of California.
His fellow Democrat from Ohio, Mary Kaptur, believes the same people who are pushing for action are responsible for the Wall Street crash.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared with the previous month and by 12.9 percent compared with August 2007, reports the Hungarian Central Statistical Office.
Industrial export sales prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while they decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to a year earlier.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 per cent compared with the previous month and by 3.2 per cent compared with the previous year.
Domestic industrial sales prices rose only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic sales prices in manufacturing sectors were only slightly higher by 0.1 per cent compared with July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather and footwear manufacturing sector (2,8 per cent), with the manufacturing of bags and belts rising first with a monthly increase of 4,6 per cent, followed by footwear production with a monthly increase of 2,5 per cent.
The higher price level of raw materials in plastics and chemicals has led to a considerable monthly increase in prices in the manufacturing sector of products and chemicals (1.6%).
This resulted in deflation in the oil processing sector (1.4 per cent), in the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.9 per cent) and a slight increase in the wood processing sector (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper production, printing and printing activities have not changed.
The other sectors of the manufacturing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a large share of the national industrial operation, prices rose by 0.3 per cent in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales in the processing sector, the oil processing sector saw the most significant increase in prices (32.4%).
In the metal manufacturing sector, prices rose by 13.2%, while in the important food, beverage and tobacco sector prices rose by 11%.
Prices fell in the textile and textile products industries (2.5%) and in the manufacture of machinery and electrical equipment (0.3%).
In the other sectors of manufacturing, the price increase was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
In the manufacturing industry as a whole, prices rose by 10.2 per cent last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7 per cent higher than in the previous year.
Among the groups of domestic trade and by sectoral breakdown, the sectors generating the highest monthly price increases (0.7%) were those generating the highest profit on investment in August.
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices rose by 0.3%, while those in the energy and materials for further processing sectors were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared with the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy production and materials for further processing sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was 6.8 per cent, while in the profit-making sectors it was 1.4 per cent.
Export sales prices in the industrial sector, in HUF, increased by 1.1 per cent in August compared with the previous month, while they fell by 3.9 per cent over 12 months.
In one month, our national currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro and 7.1 percent against the dollar, and compared with August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
