Járóka said: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit on Equal Opportunities, hosted by France, as representative of the current Presidency of the European Union, opened in Paris.
In her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers for the expert consultation, Lívia Járóka, MEP for Fidesz European People's Party, drew attention to segregation in education, as it is a violation of the right that most affects Roma children and therefore one of the main obstacles to their success in life.
On behalf of the French Presidency, the high-level conference was opened by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Labour and Social Affairs, and Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner for Labour, Social Affairs and Equal Opportunities.
The consultation will include the European social partners, as well as the most prominent representatives of legal protection and European civil society organisations in the field of equal opportunities.
According to the press office of the Fidesz People's Party group, Járóka warned that apart from the distinctions observed in hiring, Roma are disappearing from the labour market primarily as a result of their low qualifications.
"The overwhelming majority of Roma youths do not have a secondary school diploma, and as a result of poor quality primary education, only a small proportion have the opportunity to obtain a higher education diploma".
Járóka also stressed that education as a basic human right plays a key role in the enforcement of other fundamental rights.
Investing in early childhood education for Roma children means strengthening the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
The Commission is also proposing to increase the number of EU-funded projects in the field of education and training.
The earlier a Roma child starts school, the more likely he is to become a productive member of the labour market; by means of taxes paid on his income and consumption, he contributes to the state budget.
"Given their European Union citizenship, Roma must be guaranteed their right to quality education and protected from low-quality and sectarian education", stressed Lívia Járóka.
The MEPs also stressed that the EU should work together to ensure that the EU's policy on education and training is implemented in a way that is consistent with the principles of the European Union.
'The vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment must be broken, and Roma children must be given the opportunities provided by democracy so that they can participate as full citizens in the future of Europe,' he said.
In the name of the European Year for Equal Opportunities for All, the aim of the Summit on Equal Opportunities in Europe, which has been held annually since the Berlin Summit last year, is to provide a single platform to support measures taken at European and Member State level to promote equal opportunities and fight discrimination.
