No opposition MPs have entered the Belarusian parliament since Sunday's election.
According to Russian observers, this is due to a country led by Alexander Lukashenko, which provides prosperity and stability, while according to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), this is due to illegal voting.
The OSCE, which sent 450 observers from 43 countries, does not recognize the elections.
Although the 110-member legislature in this country of 10 million people has been doing very well in opposition for decades, before yesterday's elections, the opposition uniting forces under the name of United Democratic Forces (UDFZ) had serious hopes that Lukashenko, renewing his presidential term for the fourth time in a dubious election, following the amendment of the constitution in 2006, would "allow" the presence of some opposition MPs in parliament this time.
In this way, the ODSZ has abandoned its originally planned boycott.
The fact that Belarus, which is increasingly economically dependent on Russia, would like to improve its relations with the EU, where because of the Belarusian political order described as undemocratic, Lukashenko and several high-ranking politicians are not granted visas, was one of the opposition's expectations.
The fact that the OSCE, in evaluating the campaign, emphasized positive changes rather than shortcomings, such as the prohibition of running for one third of the opposition candidates, referred to a prior appeasement.
However, the OSCE statement on Monday already contested the campaign, during which most of the opposition candidates could not appear in the media, and particularly the fact that the opposition could not be present at the counting of the votes.
Despite all this, the opposition is still feeling a tangible improvement in the political regime: political prisoners have been released, and Minsk is ready for small confrontations with Moscow, still refusing to recognize South Ossetia and Abkhazia as separate from Georgia.
"We have taken two steps forward, and one step back, but the most important thing is that dialogue has begun between Belarus and the EU", Alexander Milinkevitch told our newspaper.
According to the opposition candidate in the 2006 presidential election, it is desirable that this should remain the case, despite the fact that "the government has been afraid in this parliament, which has no weight, to bring in even a single opponent".
The opposition is not planning protests in light of the results, but is trying to get its message about the need for economic reforms to the voters.
"Of course, we have a lot of concerns on that side: we have to have our opposition newspapers printed in Russia, the local authorities are putting sticks in our wheels for distribution, but I can also see that they are increasingly supporting the elections, even among the elderly", Milinkevitch said, referring to the fact that under the current Lukashenko regime, which considers social security as its main result, the most officially supported layer of pensioners no longer really consider it appropriate.
"Because of the country's debt and growing trade deficit, the collapse of social security, 'like a cemetery's silence,' is only a matter of time", says Milinkevitch.
Unlike the opposition politician, Russian observers described the elections as democratic.
Sergey Lebedev, head of the Commonwealth of Independent States mission, told the Russian news agency Ria Novosti: "People don't believe in words, but in deeds".
