Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the heavy use of portable music devices and the increasing number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
'The scientists confirm that there is good reason for concern and that the European Commission will now examine with Member States and other interested parties what measures could possibly be taken to better protect children and adolescents from exposure to noise from portable music and similar devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
It is possible to reduce this data considerably by using solutions such as reducing levels and duration of exposure to noise.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (over 89 decibels) for 5 hours a week, exceed the current limits on the maximum permissible noise level in the workplace.
People who listen to music in such conditions for long periods of time are at risk of permanent hearing loss after five years.
This concerns 5-10% of users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
The Commission has been asked to leave Rome for the future of the capital.
Today we start, in March we finish, in June we draw the sums.
This is the schedule set by the Capitol for the work of the "Commission for the Future of Rome Capital", which took place this morning at the new headquarters behind the Baths of Caracalla.
In six months' time, President Antonio Marzano and the other 49 members of the Commission will draw up the guidelines for Rome.
In March, when they are completed, the Committee and the Municipal Council will evaluate the analyses and projects, in order to present in June the Strategic Plan for Rome with the "official stamp" of the Capitol and its mayor Gianni Alemanno.
"The committee is absolutely independent; all political, social and cultural ideas are represented", Alemanno stressed.
No overlapping of roles, but only the desire to have a corner to work out a big project for Rome.
In March, it will have completed its tasks and then disappear, because this experiment must have a precise time duration.
In June, the mayor announced, we will present the strategic plan for the future of Rome Capital, based on the work of the Commission".
To those who accuse the Commission of being useless, since its opinions will not be binding, Alemanno replies: 'Everything depends on the work the Commission will be able to do and the quality of its proposals.
If quality is there, as in France thanks to the Attali Commission, as in Rome, I am sure his contribution will be fundamental.
Too often, politics is overwhelmed by the day-to-day management and the occasional emergencies.
We, on the contrary, want to look ahead, and further, to a deeper perspective, working seriously for the development of Rome and its future".
The Mayor of Rome also emphasised that 'this Commission is not a useless body or a bureaucratic setup: it is absolutely free, and will not cost the citizens of Rome a single euro, and will serve to study and involve the best minds who express the Capital.
For Alemanno, "a strategic reference framework, neither firm nor immobile, is needed to enable our city to improve, which it absolutely needs, while thinking about its future with a united spirit".
A future which, the mayor of Rome said, "will not be limited to the usual municipal boundaries but look further afield, not only in terms of the future metropolitan city and its legal status as capital, but also in relation to the role that Rome can and must play as the capital of Europe and the Mediterranean".
