The elite are in danger.
This was already evident a few days ago when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion bailout approved by the White House: a significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is the New York Times yesterday that confirms this, reporting that the current crisis is dividing the Republican Party, even more divided between its old, moderate East Coast soul, which is supportive of federal institutions and the business community, and its new, conservative soul, which is hostile to the Washington establishment and the financial world, which is especially powerful in the Central and Southern states.
The spirit, precisely, which was made to feel in a despotic way with the vote that I told you about at the beginning.
But what has just been said is just one example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake is heralding or is already setting in motion: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not just here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to be accelerating the phenomena which have been brewing for some time, to the point that in the new climate they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival, of the dual category of State and sovereign, as opposed to a kind of renationalisation of the economy.
The crisis is a crisis of banking and financial institutions which have obviously close relations with foreign countries, but which are above all involved on a large scale, the balances of individuals and families living in one country, in one state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears to be economically global but politically it is almost only domestic.
Political internationalisation seems to be out of the question or not at all: the clear proof is the European Union, which, as usual, is divided between different interests and national strategies and cannot decide on a common policy.
And so it is from the governments of each State that all expect interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all a loan: when you go through a difficult period, only the States have the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things right.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two invaluable resources, which no market or international organization can ever have in a comparable way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the ever-greater importance which more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attach to a factor quite closely linked to this element: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of the non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we suddenly realized that our future would instead have to settle its accounts more and more with the rather non-material things like water, crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but that are absolutely bound to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
So whoever is sovereign certainly has more cards than whoever is not, that is, whoever is unlucky enough to live in a place without crops, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second new feature which, however, involves a fracture.
What says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for someone who can take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, there is a wave of discredit for existing leadership, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of shadow.
And then there's something even deeper, in a sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of alienation that tends to involve the entire executive class in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be increasingly alien to the opinions of the majority, increases even more.
In short, the demand for leadership underground fuels a powerful and branching movement of delegitimizations of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifests itself in the improvised electoral "riots" or, in the recent changes in collective moods, from the rise of conservatism in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of Labour in Britain, to the rebellion of US Congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not come by chance).
It seems that the traditional elites, their parties, their programmes, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, some would say, are having increasing difficulty, which is not new, in understanding and therefore representing the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is strengthening, growing and potentially agitating in an unreasonable way.
In view of all this, it seems frankly exaggerated to talk about a current "mass revolt" on the agenda.
But as they say, keeping your eyes peeled is not without reason.
The super glue to walk on walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various research centers in the United States, and today a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
Using a piece of adhesive that was only 2.5 square centimeters, researchers were able to hold a 100-kilogram body on a vertical wall.
The study was published in the journal Science by researchers at the University of Dayton, the University of Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology, and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the research team, is an evolution of the ones we know that use a special carbon structure, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be thought of as a series of tubes arranged like a stack of spaghetti", explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
Scientists have taken inspiration from the geckos' legs, which are covered in microscopic hairs that help ensure that the animal adheres perfectly.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and glass foil, showed that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time, it can easily peel off the wall", says Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
"This material could be used as a temporary adhesive", adds Liming Dai.
Maybe walking on walls like Spiderman? Maybe, but researchers think of a much less fascinating use, like connecting electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
No superheroes at the moment.
Another research team at the University of California, Berkeley, is also working on a new adhesive.
In an article in the American Chemical Society, researchers in California presented a glue made of hairlike microfibers that cleans itself of dust when moving on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Be careful with grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, which are consumed mainly in summer because they are thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, when combined with certain vital medicines, alter their absorption, increasing or decreasing their effectiveness, depending on the case, with even serious health consequences.
David Nailey, a professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, warns of the dangers of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, when they are associated with ingestion of certain medicines. At the 236th National Meeting of the American Chemical Society in Philadelphia, he raises a new alarm: one glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice is enough to reduce the absorption of some vital medicines, negating their beneficial effects and putting patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for being responsible for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, anti-stamina and neurological medications to toxic levels.
RISKED MEDICINES - The Italian Medicines Agency itself reported the news in a newsletter two years ago, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger of this mixture and to be careful what they drink if they are taking drugs such as Diazepam or Methadone.
Not just the pepper - According to experts, even orange juice and apple juice contain substances that inhibit medication.
There is a long list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
The Commission has therefore decided to initiate a review of the information provided by the Member States on the use of the drug in the Community.
It is always good to read the package leaflet of the medicines you are taking and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist", the expert told Ansa.
