Open Office, this is the third edition of the anti-Microsoft package.
Today is the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source suite for personal productivity that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
After almost a year of work by volunteer developers, supervised by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is presented to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen, the revised and less austere interface, to other more important ones, such as the compatibility born for the Apple Mac OS X operating system, and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the Office 2007 suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some functions specific to certain modules, such as the one that allows you to reduce the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into the graphics development module, keeping the original appearance of the page.
On this front too, it is possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents that combine typical Adobe graphics with elements of a spreadsheet or word processor.
Multi-person collaboration is an element that has seen various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts over edits, in the preparation of texts, because each collaborator is assigned a comment color for better recognition during the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some of the OpenOffice functions to the web, and in the coming weeks they should be releasing the final result.
The Italian version is available for download at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet and is in addition to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual available for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be sent to your home or workplace.
And if the theme of free can be a way to spread it in the home, it is precisely in business that Open Office next tries the big challenge, already counting on various projects carried out in public administration and schools.
This is not to mention the fact that they offer training, consultancy and assistance services, ideal for small and mediumsized enterprises, which could also open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for the video equivalent of Word; Calc, the spreadsheet that replaces Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint's rival presentations; Dbase, like the famous Access, is the program that allows you to work on databases; and Drwa is the graphics module.
The target for 2008 is 5 million downloads, and considering that today we have almost 3 million and 600 miles, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the expected figure.
