Goodbye old Paradiso cinema, the cities are emitting historic theaters.
The historic movie theaters are closing in favor of the multiplexes.
"A city without cinemas is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image, by director Giuseppe Tornatore, is a good example of what is happening in the major Italian urban centres, but also in the provincial towns,
The process of marginalisation of cinemas, with the emergence of large multi-screen cinemas on the outskirts and the death of single-screen cinemas in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events which seems inevitable and indisputable to us.
The disappearance of historical places is often a memory-laden event, "it is as if a friend of mine disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a journey and so many emotions", says the director of Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that won Tornatore its first Oscar and the Grand Prix of the Cannes Jury 20 years ago, and which told the story of the poetry of a provincial cinema, and the nostalgia for a way of living the cinema, lost forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main trade association, tell the whole story: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and the main city cinemas have paid the most: 10 fewer in Florence, 9 fewer in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 fewer in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Emilia-Romagna leads with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The first proof that the multiplex is responsible for their disappearance is the advent of multiplexes, as the three Italian regions have the most new multi-screen cinemas: 195 in Lombardy over the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"The Italian operation has grown irrationally", says Paolo Protti, president of Anec. "It is useful to build new facilities, but the survival of existing ones must still be guaranteed, because when a theatre closes in a city, not all of these visitors are necessarily willing to go to the multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation on the credit to the merchants: the previous state debt is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that from an ethical and moral point of view the Government does not respect the existing laws.
The support for the sector is estimated to be between EUR 16 and 18 million per year.
The first Italian city to address the problem of the closure was Bologna, which decided to sign a protocol between the city council and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-screen cinemas in the historic centre and on the outskirts.
The proposed rules include tax incentives for managers and mobility benefits for the public: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone and will have special rates for parking and in some car parks.
"I welcome this initiative", says Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna's example and implement other measures.
It is clear, however, that to counter the superpower of multiplexes, traditional theatres must also improve the quality of sound and picture, as today's audiences are more demanding.
The defence of traditional cinema is a theme that has always been important to me: the closure of the Supercinema de Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" which I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I've lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the now-closed Quirinal de Via Nazionale, where I've lived so many shared emotions, I turn the other way so as not to see the signs blackened by dust.
