When energy comes from waves, now the big ones go.
This is an enormous deposit that covers over 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources that giants like Chevron have set their sights on, and now are trying to get their hands on.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movement of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now, and in the 1970s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was put aside, but now environmental concerns and the new increase in oil are giving a big boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity needs could be met by offshore systems.
This would be twice as much as the amount produced by nuclear power plants.
And then there would be the currents and the tides.
Colossus is on the attack.
The first company to invest in marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a facility in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it would have seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years on, more and more of these companies, which have always been committed to traditional energy, are turning to marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies", a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal, "and is evaluating opportunities to work with us".
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit from the US Energy Commission, which is necessary to develop a marine energy project in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially when you consider that in Alaska, the United States is still drilling for oil, and recently President Bush has put in place a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, there are Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey, which are exploring the sea energy route, and the amounts invested to date, although details are unknown, indicate, according to observers, a growing interest.
Technology to be developed.
Experts say the technology is still in its infancy, partly because marine energy is not allaying fears about environmental impact.
At present, systems like those in Portugal, or some in Scotland, are small in size, and do not seem to pose a major problem to the ecosystem.
However, large-scale energy production requires the use of technologies with a higher environmental impact.
And the choices are diverse: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of interconnected buoys.
The wave force, which moves the mud up and down, is converted into hydraulic pressure from the pistons and cylinders inside the floats.
The pressure drives a turbine, which in turn, powers a generator.
The power is sent to the shore through undersea cables.
We have four such systems in the design phase, pending a single federal approval, and some of the energy could be used for a military facility.
Verdant Power, by contrast, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot using six underwater turbines on the East River in New York.
The movement of water at high tide, turns the blades of the turbines, creating a rotating motion that powers a generator.
Verdant has announced that it has a long list of customers waiting for the necessary permits to draw energy.
After the waves, the tides.
Particular interest, they say at the Institute for Electrical Energy Research, is now due to the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, the tide is more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and thus more reliable as a source of energy.
And it's precisely on tidal energy that states like New York, Maine and Alaska, among others, looking to the coast, invested $7.5 million in 2008 and are planning to invest up to $35 million in 2009.
